    "The samples i d should characterize zero risk if the associated d gt is indeed collision-free.",
    "On the other hand, the samples should lead to a high risk value if d gt is insufficient for collision avoidance.",
    "We can interpret this requirement as a two class classification problem conditioned on the samples i d and implicitly on the predicted variance σ θ (u, o).",
    "The risk estimation head of Fig. 5 performs exactly this role.The risk estimation head estimates collision constraint vio-Algorithm 1: Sampling-Based Optimizer to Solve (1a)-(1b)1 M = Maximum number of iterations 2 Initiate mean m ν, m Σ, at iteration m = 0 for sampling control inputs u; Given observation vector o, trained neural network θ(Fig.",
    "5)3 for m = 1, m ≤ M, m + + do 4 Initialize CostList = [] 5 Draw batch of n control sequences (u 1, u 2, u q,...., u n) from N ( m ν, m Σ) 6Query collision model ∀u q: (µ θ,q, σ θ,q, λ θ,q) = MLP θ (u q, o) // MLP θ denotes the learned model whose output µ θ,q, σ θ,q, λ θ,q denotes the predicted mean, predicted variance and the kernel parameter, respectively, for each control sequence u q 7Compute N distance samples i d q ∼ N (µ q, σ q), ∀i = 1,..., N and subsequently N constraint violation samples i h q. Repeat this process ∀q = (1, 2,..., n) // i d q denotes i-th obstacle clearance sample corresponding to the q-th control sequence."
